==German==

===Etymology===
Possibly from the {{etyl|pox|de}} stem {{term|berl-|lang=pox}} / {{term|birl-||swamp|lang=pox}} + suffix {{term|-in|lang=pox}}. The place is first mentioned by this name in the late 12th century (as {{term|Berlyn|lang=gml}}). According to (incorrect) [[folk etymology]], the name is derived from the {{term|Bär||bear|lang=de}} that is the symbol of the city.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|Standard New High German}} {{IPA|[bɛɐˈliːn]|[bɛʁˈliːn]|lang=de}},
* {{a|Berlinisch}} {{IPA|[baliːn]|[baliːən]|lang=de}}
*: {{Audio|De-Berlin-pronunciation.ogg|Audio (Berlin)}}

===Proper noun===
{{infl|de|noun|g=n}}

# [[Berlin#English|Berlin]], the capital city of Germany.
#: '''Berlin''' ist mehr ein Weltteil als eine Stadt. &mdash; Johann Paul Friedrich Richter, '''1800'''.
#:: '''''Berlin''' is more a ''part of a world'' than a ''city''.''
#: '''Berlin''' ist eine Stadt, verdammt dazu, ewig zu werden, niemals zu sein. &mdash; Karl Scheffler, author of ''Berlin: Ein Stadtschicksal'', '''1910'''.
#:: '''''Berlin''' is a city damned forever to [[become]], never to [[be]].''
